Write the prose for ONE passage. {{ words_min }}-{{ words_max }} words of finished,
publishable markdown paragraphs (no headings, no lists). This is the passage the
player reads. Everything below is context; each block says what it is FOR and
what you may do with it — none of it may leak as jargon, and none of it is
material to copy: the only prose in this prompt is prose the reader has
already read.

VOICE (binding — this owns how everything sounds):
- POV: {{ voice.pov }} | tense: {{ voice.tense }} | diction: {{ voice.diction }}
- Rhythm: {{ voice.rhythm }}
{% if voice.imagery %}
- Imagery: {{ voice.imagery }}
{% endif %}
{% if voice.dialogue %}
- Dialogue: {{ voice.dialogue }}
{% endif %}
- Banned: {{ voice.banned | join("; ") }}
- Notes: {{ voice.notes }}
When you need a description, reach for the voice's imagery palette — sparingly,
at the charged moments named below, never as the default texture of every
sentence — and never for the wording of a fact or a phrase from an earlier
passage.

STYLE BELONGS TO THE STORY, NOT TO THIS PARAGRAPH. The VOICE above is how the
whole book sounds across its arc — it is not a quota to hit in every sentence.
Write most of this passage as plain, clear, load-bearing prose: a straightforward
grammatical spine — who does what, what happens next — that a reader navigating
choices can follow without effort. Reach for the voice's heightened register (its
imagery, its most distinctive cadence, its richest diction) at only a FEW charged
moments here — an opening image, the beat this scene turns on, the last line — and
let the prose between them stay unadorned. A passage where every sentence strains
for effect is OVER-WRITTEN: it reads as airless and exhausting even when each line
is fine in isolation, and it is the most common prose failure at book scale. So do
not open a fresh metaphor or coin a new compound in every clause; do not dissolve
the prose into a strobe of short fragments; keep sentences complete and varied in
length. Clarity outranks atmosphere — after reading, a player must be able to say
plainly what just happened.

{% if interlude %}
THIS PASSAGE IS AN INTERLUDE — a marked deviation from the book's base narration:
{{ voice.interlude or "a first-person reflective piece in the viewpoint character's own voice" }}
Write the whole passage in that register — its person, tense, and form override
the VOICE's pov and tense above for this passage only (the review judges it
against this register, not the book default). It is still ONE mind on the page:
{% if viewpoint %}{{ viewpoint.name }}'s{% else %}the named narrator's{% endif %} — the no-other-minds rule below still holds.
{% else %}
TENSE IS ABSOLUTE: narrate in {{ voice.tense }} tense, every verb, start to
finish — the review checks this verb by verb and it is the most common failure.
Events that happened before this moment are still told in {{ voice.tense }}: a
present-tense voice renders a prior event in the present perfect or simple
present ("has vanished", "vanishes"), never the simple past ("vanished"). Read
your first sentence back before anything else — that is where the wrong tense
slips in.
{% endif %}

POINT OF VIEW — TWO SEPARATE RULES:
1. NO OTHER MINDS. {% if viewpoint %}THIS passage's viewpoint character is
   {{ viewpoint.name }} ({{ viewpoint.id }}): the reader is inside {{ viewpoint.name }}'s
   mind and no other, whatever heads other passages use — the VOICE above names the
   book's scheme; this line names the head that scheme assigns HERE.{% else %}The
   POV above fixes whose mind the reader is inside.{% endif %} Only that
   narrator's thoughts, intentions, and feelings may be stated directly. Every
   other character reaches the reader only through what the narrator can observe —
   their actions, their speech, their expression. When a beat or an ARC POSITION
   below describes another character's plan or state ("she intends to…", "he has
   decided…"), that is a brief for what they DO in this scene, not a licence to
   enter their mind: render it as observable behavior. Stating a non-narrator
   character's interiority is the most common POV break and fails review (rule 1).
2. DISTANCE MAY WIDEN. Being limited does NOT confine the narration to the
   character's immediate sensation. The narrator may still report a world fact they
   could plausibly know — the weather, a rumor, the shape of a place, an event they
   witness or infer — in a wider, more summary register. Reporting the world is not
   a POV break; entering another mind is. (A beat marked a `wide` coda below goes
   further still — see INTENSITY & SCOPE.)

PASSAGE {{ passage.id }}{% if passage.ending %} — ENDING "{{ passage.ending.title }}"{% endif %} — overall a {{ intensity }} passage:
summary: {{ passage.summary }}
Realize these beats, in order, as one continuous scene. The summaries are your
brief, not your style: take the events, stakes, and mood they name; leave their
wording behind — the VOICE above, not the summary, owns how anything sounds.
Each beat is tagged with its INTENSITY (where the prose may rise) and its SCOPE
(whether it stays inside the POV or is a detached coda):
{% for b in beats %}
- [{{ beat_scene[b.id] }} · {{ beat_scope[b.id] }}] {{ b.summary }}
{% endfor %}
INTENSITY makes "style belongs to the story" concrete per beat: a `scene` beat is
active conflict — the turn this passage exists for, where the heightened register
may come out and the words may run a little longer. A `sequel` beat is reactive —
a character absorbing what just happened; write it plain and brief. A `micro_beat`
is a transition; keep it to the fewest clear sentences. Most beats are not scenes —
hold the ornament for the ones that are.
SCOPE tells you the POV frame per beat: a `limited` beat obeys the POV rules above
(no other minds, distance may widen). A `wide` beat is a CODA — you may step back
to a detached register and narrate what the viewpoint character could not know:
world aftermath, a fate that plays out beyond this scene, a character's reputation
after they are gone. Write the shift cleanly at the paragraph — a limited scene may
close into a wide coda — never as a mid-sentence leap. Do not widen a `limited`
beat this way; the coda license belongs only to `wide`.

CAST IN SCENE — facts are CONSTRAINTS, not choreography. Every fact below is
already established: the scene must not contradict it, and the reader already
knows it. Never restate a fact's wording (this is checked and rejected). Spend
words on a fact only when this scene turns on it, and then in fresh words;
otherwise it stays background — a fact honored silently is honored best:
{% for e in entities %}
- {{ e.name }} ({{ e.id }}){% if e.pronouns %} — PRONOUNS: {{ e.pronouns }}, exactly{% endif %}: {{ e.concept }}{% if e.base %} | facts: {% for k, v in e.base.items() %}{{ k }}: {{ v }}; {% endfor %}{% endif %}
{% if e.overlays %}
{% for o in e.overlays %}
  - when {{ o.when | join(" & ") }}: {% for k, v in o.details.items() %}{{ k }}: {{ v }}; {% endfor %}
{% endfor %}
{% endif %}
{% endfor %}

{% if arcs %}
ARC POSITION (who each of these is RIGHT NOW — the one aspect this scene may
foreground; every established fact outside it stays background). For anyone but
the narrator this is what the scene must SHOW through their behavior, never
state as their thoughts (see POINT OF VIEW above):
{% for a in arcs %}
- {{ a.entity.name }}: {{ a.now }}{% if a.turn %} — THIS SCENE TURNS IT: {{ a.turn }}{% endif %}{% if a.heading %} (heading toward: {{ a.heading }} — do not arrive early){% endif %}{% for s in a.ends %} | this route has committed: {{ s }}{% endfor %}
{% endfor %}
{% endif %}

WORLD STATE AT THIS PASSAGE — only CERTAIN facts may be stated as true:
{% for f in flags %}
- {{ f.flag.description }} — {{ f.status }}
{% endfor %}
{% if not flags %}
- nothing committed yet
{% endif %}
A POSSIBLE fact is true on some routes here and false on others: NEVER depict
it happening, name its result, or let the narration assume it — a reader who
did not reach it must find no contradiction. Do not reach for it to fill a
scene; write around it so the passage reads true either way. State only what is
CERTAIN. (This is checked: asserting a possible state as fact fails review.)

THE ROADS NOT TAKEN (shadows — let their weight color the prose, never name them):
{% for s in shadows %}
- {{ s.dilemma.question }} {% for a in s.answers %}[{{ a.text }}{% if not a.explored %} — never explored{% endif %}] {% endfor %}
{% endfor %}

{% if story_so_far %}
THE STORY SO FAR (one route to this passage, in notes — context, not material:
the reader lived these events, so the prose may lean on them without retelling
them. Other routes exist, and an event particular to this one may not have
happened for every reader — WORLD STATE above governs what you may assert):
{% if story_elided %}
- (… {{ story_elided }} earlier passages elided)
{% endif %}
{% for s in story_so_far %}
- {{ s }}
{% endfor %}
{% endif %}

{% if window %}
WHAT THE READER JUST READ (continuity, not a style template): continue from it
seamlessly — its events happened, its objects and weather persist. Do not
reuse its imagery or repeat its phrasing; the reader just read those words,
and a lifted run is rejected. A neighbor told from a DIFFERENT viewpoint is
still continuity of events — but its narrator's interiority stays there; this
passage opens fresh inside its own head:
{% for w in window %}
--- from {{ w.passage.id }} (arrived via "{{ w.label }}"{% if w.head and (not viewpoint or w.head != viewpoint.name) %}; told from {{ w.head }}'s viewpoint{% endif %}):
{{ w.passage.prose }}
{% endfor %}
{% endif %}
{% if lookahead %}
WHAT AWAITS (already written — land so it follows naturally, without echoing it):
{% for w in lookahead %}
--- toward {{ w.passage.id }} (via "{{ w.label }}"{% if w.head and (not viewpoint or w.head != viewpoint.name) %}; told from {{ w.head }}'s viewpoint{% endif %}):
{{ w.passage.prose }}
{% endfor %}
{% endif %}

{% if not window and not lookahead %}
