The rejection list below carries the reasons this draft was rejected. Most are
FINDINGS, labeled [rule · ASSESSMENT · confidence] — including a `word_budget`
finding when the prose is outside its length band, and an `overwriting` finding
when it coins too many hyphen-compounds (say most of them plainly). A FINDING
marked FAIL is blocking — resolve each; a FINDING marked WARN, or one of low
confidence, is a concern to weigh and decide, not a mandate — do not over-correct.
A rejection with no such label (a lifted phrase) is a hard requirement: fix it.
For EVERY item in the list add one `revision_notes` entry: {"finding": quote or
name the item, "how_addressed": the exact change you make to THIS draft to
resolve it}. Do not re-derive the prose and hope it lands: decide the change
first — for a length finding, name WHICH beat or moment you expand or tighten
and by roughly how much (a shortfall is fixed by deepening a beat the draft
rushed, never by padding) — state it in the note, then write prose that delivers
it. The reviewer checks each note against the text, so a claimed change your
prose does not make is worse than none.
{% endif %}
